                <h1>The Causes of World War I: Understanding the Triggers</h1>
                <p>World War I was precipitated by a complex interplay of factors, including militarism, alliances, imperialism, and nationalism. The immediate catalyst was the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary in 1914, which triggered pre-existing tensions among European powers and resulted in a widespread conflict that engulfed multiple nations.</p>
